"Budge K., Leifeld J., Hiltbrunner E., Fuhrer J.","Alpine grassland soils contain large proportion of labile carbon but indicate long turnover times",2011,"Biogeosciences","8","7",,"1911","1923",,,10.5194/bg-8-1911-2011,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79960609710&partnerID=40&md5=c47051d9743f253b6eee6bf7826c25ed","Air Pollution/Climate Group, Agroscope Reckenholz-Tänikon Research Station ART, Reckenholzstrasse 191, 8046 Zurich, Switzerland; Institute of Botany, University of Basel, Schünbeinstrasse 6, 4056 Basel, Switzerland","Budge, K., Air Pollution/Climate Group, Agroscope Reckenholz-Tänikon Research Station ART, Reckenholzstrasse 191, 8046 Zurich, Switzerland; Leifeld, J., Air Pollution/Climate Group, Agroscope Reckenholz-Tänikon Research Station ART, Reckenholzstrasse 191, 8046 Zurich, Switzerland; Hiltbrunner, E., Institute of Botany, University of Basel, Schünbeinstrasse 6, 4056 Basel, Switzerland; Fuhrer, J., Air Pollution/Climate Group, Agroscope Reckenholz-Tänikon Research Station ART, Reckenholzstrasse 191, 8046 Zurich, Switzerland","Alpine soils are expected to contain large amounts of labile carbon (C) which may become a further source of atmospheric carbon dioxide (CO 2) as a result of global warming. However, there is little data available on these soils, and understanding of the influence of environmental factors on soil organic matter (SOM) turnover is limited. We extracted 30 cm deep cores from five grassland sites along a small elevation gradient from 2285 to 2653 m a.s.l. in the central Swiss Alps. Our aim was to determine the quantity, allocation, degree of stabilization and mean residence time (MRT) of SOM in relation to site factors such as soil pH, vegetation, and SOM composition. Soil fractions obtained by size and density fractionation revealed a high proportion of labile C in SOM, mostly in the uppermost soil layers. Labile C in the top 20 cm across the gradient ranged from 39.6ĝ€""57.6 % in comparison to 7.2ĝ€""29.6 % reported in previous studies for lower elevation soils (810ĝ€""1960 m a.s.l.). At the highest elevation, MRTs measured by means of radiocarbon dating and turnover modelling, increased between fractions of growing stability from 90 years in free POM (fPOM) to 534 years in the mineral associated fraction (mOM). Depending on elevation and pH, plant community data suggested considerable variation in the quantity and quality of organic matter input, and these patterns could be reflected in the dynamics of soil C. 13C NMR data confirmed a relationship of SOM composition to MRT. While low temperature in alpine environments is likely to be a major cause for the slow turnover rate observed, other factors such as residue quality and soil pH, as well as the combination of all factors, play an important role in causing small scale variability of SOM turnover. Failing to incorporate this interplay of controlling factors into models may impair the performance of models to project SOM responses to environmental change. © 2010 Author(s).",,"alpine environment; carbon dioxide; data set; environmental change; environmental factor; fractionation; global warming; grassland; nuclear magnetic resonance; numerical model; observational method; pH; plant community; radiocarbon dating; soil carbon; soil organic matter; soil type; stabilization; vegetation structure; Alps; Switzerland",,,,,,"Ammann, C., Spirig, C., Leifeld, J., Neftel, A., Assessment of the nitrogen and carbon budget of two managed temperate grassland fields (2009) Agric. Ecosyst. Environ., 133, pp. 150-162; Baisden, W.T., Amundson, R., Cook, A.C., Brenner, D.L., Turnover and storage of C and N in five density fractions from California annual grassland surface soil (2002) Global Biogeochem. Cy., 16, pp. 1117-1132; Baldock, J.A., Oades, J.M., Nelson, P.N., Skene, T.M., Golchin, A., Clarke, P., Assessing the extent of decomposition of natural organic materials using solid-state 13C NMR spectroscopy (2007) Aust. J. Soil Res., 35